10:36.233 --> 10:40.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: At a movie
theater in Seoul, South Korea,
screens flashed the bad news:

10:41.633 --> 10:44.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
now playing, a
global cyber-attack.

10:44.400 --> 10:49.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Indonesia, the waiting room
at a cancer hospital in Jakarta
was packed with patients,

10:50.866 --> 10:53.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
their records also held hostage
by this so-called ransomware.

10:53.666 --> 10:57.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN (through translator):
There are always so many people.

10:57.900 --> 10:59.466 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
That's why it's taking so long.

10:59.466 --> 11:01.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We're tired, but we
need the treatment.

11:01.966 --> 11:06.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: In
China, state media reported
some 4,000 schools were
among the hardest-hit

11:07.966 --> 11:10.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
there, including two
prestigious universities.

11:10.433 --> 11:12.866 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WANG WENYI, Chinese
National Computer
Response Center (through
translator): If we pay the

11:12.866 --> 11:17.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ransom, then we are risking
getting our personal
information, including
our account information,

11:17.200 --> 11:19.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
recorded and stolen.

11:19.666 --> 11:22.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Japanese
companies Hitachi and
Nissan were affected
as well, but Japan's

11:22.766 --> 11:25.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
chief cabinet secretary
said the damage was minimal.

11:25.666 --> 11:30.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The virus first struck on
Friday, primarily at hospitals
in Britain and companies across

11:31.300 --> 11:33.833 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Europe.

11:33.833 --> 11:37.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This particular kind of
ransomware takes advantage
of a security flaw in
Microsoft's Windows

11:37.000 --> 11:39.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
operating system.

11:39.000 --> 11:42.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It locks users out of their
computers until they pay
a ransom to get it back.

11:42.700 --> 11:47.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This strain of ransomware was
apparently built in part using
software created by the National

11:47.233 --> 11:52.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Security Agency, the NSA, which
was then stolen by hackers.

11:52.200 --> 11:56.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Microsoft patched the flaw in
its system in March, but many
users either ignored it or

11:56.233 --> 11:58.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
refused to pay for it.

11:58.266 --> 12:02.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In an open letter Sunday,
Microsoft President Brad Smith
blamed the NSA and called it yet

12:05.033 --> 12:08.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
another example of
why the stockpiling
of vulnerabilities by
governments is such a problem.

12:11.100 --> 12:14.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Russian President Vladimir
Putin, who is visiting
China, also criticized
the U.S., amid reports

12:15.866 --> 12:17.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that his interior ministry
had been hit hard.

12:17.900 --> 12:20.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
VLADIMIR PUTIN, Russian
President (through
translator): The primary
source of the virus

12:20.000 --> 12:23.566 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
happens to be the intelligence
services of the United States.

12:23.566 --> 12:26.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Russia here is
absolutely uninvolved.

12:26.133 --> 12:29.400 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: But at
the White House today,
Tom Bossert, President
Trump's homeland security

12:29.400 --> 12:34.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
adviser, said the NSA had
never intended its tool to
be used by foreign criminals.

12:34.200 --> 12:36.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TOM BOSSERT, White House
Homeland Security Adviser: This
was a vulnerability exploit

12:36.366 --> 12:41.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as one part of a much larger
tool that was put together by
the culpable parties and not

12:41.166 --> 12:42.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
by the U.S. government.

12:42.700 --> 12:46.700 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, this wasn't a tool developed
by the NSA to hold ransom data.

12:46.700 --> 12:49.933 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Meanwhile,
there's been political fallout.

12:49.933 --> 12:54.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In Britain, where a general
election looms, opposition
leader Jeremy Corbyn and Prime

12:54.566 --> 12:57.633 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Minister Theresa May
traded jibes long-distance:

12:57.633 --> 13:01.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JEREMY CORBYN, Leader,
Labor Party: Over the
past seven years, our
National Health Service

13:01.333 --> 13:04.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
has been driven into
crisis after crisis.

13:04.900 --> 13:08.366 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
The Tory cuts have
exposed patient services
to cyber-attack.

13:08.366 --> 13:12.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
THERESA MAY, British Prime
Minister: Cyber-security is an
issue that we need to address.

13:12.833 --> 13:17.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
That's why the government, when
we came into government in 2010,
put money into cyber-security.

13:17.300 --> 13:21.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: The
cyber-attack's effects
in the United States
have been limited, except

13:21.366 --> 13:23.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
for damage to the
FedEx delivery service.

13:23.833 --> 13:26.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
For the "PBS NewsHour,"
I'm William Brangham.

13:26.133 --> 13:30.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And let's turn
to Microsoft now, which has
been responding to this attack

13:30.400 --> 13:35.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and criticizing the NSA for its
alleged role in exploiting the
vulnerability to begin with.

13:37.300 --> 13:40.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Brad Smith is the
president and chief legal
officer of the company.

13:40.733 --> 13:43.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
He joins me from
Redmond, Washington.

13:43.566 --> 13:45.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Brad Smith, welcome
back to the "NewsHour."

13:45.466 --> 13:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, first off, what is the
status of this cyber-attack?

13:48.366 --> 13:53.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There were some reports late
today about a new variant
surfacing in parts of the world.

13:53.233 --> 13:55.266 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What do you know about that?

13:55.266 --> 13:57.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
BRAD SMITH, President,
Microsoft: Well, I
think, as the report
just showed, things seem

13:57.533 --> 14:02.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
to be calming down a bit,
but it's too early to declare
victory or say that this episode

14:02.166 --> 14:03.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
is over.

14:03.666 --> 14:06.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
As you just mentioned, new
variants can be created.

14:06.000 --> 14:08.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's not uncommon in
these kinds of situations.

14:08.433 --> 14:11.000 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We will have to monitor them.

14:11.000 --> 14:15.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then, more broadly,
even as we help customers
who are dealing with
this particular attack,

14:15.800 --> 14:20.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
this is a wakeup call for all
of us, whether we're in the
tech sector, customers or in

14:20.800 --> 14:22.066 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
government.

14:22.066 --> 14:24.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We need to do more to
address this problem.

14:24.133 --> 14:28.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And you did say
in the memo that you -- that
Microsoft issued yesterday,

14:28.633 --> 14:32.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you did say this is a powerful
reminder everybody needs to
keep their computers current and

14:32.800 --> 14:34.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
patched.

14:34.800 --> 14:37.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But you did go on to point
that finger at governments
and what you call stockpiling

14:37.833 --> 14:38.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
of vulnerabilities.

14:38.833 --> 14:40.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What did you mean by that?

14:40.900 --> 14:45.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, we have been
pointing out in recent months
that, more and more, in multiple

14:45.066 --> 14:50.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
countries, certain agencies and
some governments are stockpiling
vulnerabilities, meaning the

14:51.900 --> 14:55.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
flaws That they find in
software, they're creating
their own exploits, so that they

14:56.400 --> 14:57.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have them available.

14:57.933 --> 14:59.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And this causes us concern.

14:59.600 --> 15:03.000 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We believe the world needs
some new rules to govern this.

15:03.000 --> 15:06.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We need governments to act with
restraint, and we certainly
need governments that are

15:06.800 --> 15:11.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
creating these kind
of cyber-weapons to
be effective, so that
they're not stolen or get

15:12.766 --> 15:14.800 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
leaked out.

15:14.800 --> 15:17.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, and I want
to ask you about that, because,
at the White House today,

15:17.166 --> 15:21.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the president's homeland
security adviser, Tom Bossert
-- I think you just heard him

15:21.400 --> 15:26.400 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
say this -- he said the NSA
never intended for this tool
that they created to be used

15:27.800 --> 15:30.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as part of some
ransomware attack.

15:30.600 --> 15:33.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: I think
that's got to be the case.

15:33.733 --> 15:38.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And the reality is, this
was an unusual attack.

15:38.233 --> 15:43.233 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It involved the combination
of a very sophisticated
piece of software of
the type we sometimes

15:45.300 --> 15:49.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
see in governments, then
combined with a much
less sophisticated piece
of software, in effect,

15:51.266 --> 15:53.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the ransomware component.

15:53.233 --> 15:58.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And in all probability, it's
some type of organized criminal
group that took what came

16:00.133 --> 16:04.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
out of the government and put
it to use in a way that no one
ever intended, but the damage

16:06.966 --> 16:10.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is still done, and we can't
assume that this is the last
time we will see this type of

16:10.600 --> 16:14.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
problem if we don't find
a way to take new steps.

16:14.333 --> 16:18.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, Brad
Smith, what do you say about
Microsoft's role in this?

16:18.166 --> 16:23.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm sure you know there are
security analysts out there who
are saying, not only because

16:25.633 --> 16:28.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
these flaws existed in
something that Microsoft,
that your company
created, but also that the

16:30.733 --> 16:35.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
company apparently hasn't done
enough to alert people that
these flaws are there, that they

16:36.666 --> 16:38.700 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
need to patch?

16:38.700 --> 16:41.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
There are some nonprofit
organizations, the
governments that we have
been discussing that

16:41.733 --> 16:44.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
just haven't gotten
around to it.

16:44.166 --> 16:47.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And these analysts are
saying, Microsoft should have
done more to alert people.

16:47.866 --> 16:52.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, the very
first thing that I said in my
statement yesterday was that

16:52.166 --> 16:57.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Microsoft, in fact, has
the first responsibility
to address these issues.

16:58.033 --> 16:59.700 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I think that's unquestionable.

16:59.700 --> 17:01.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We look at everything
that we're doing today.

17:01.933 --> 17:05.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We have 3,500
security engineers.

17:05.200 --> 17:09.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We worked over the
weekend to provide help to
customers around the world.

17:09.600 --> 17:13.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We acted in March
to patch software.

17:13.000 --> 17:18.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We acted in March to talk
about the importance of
this, as we do all the time.

17:19.400 --> 17:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But this is a wakeup call
for us, for customers.

17:22.200 --> 17:26.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
None of us should assume
that we're doing everything
that we can possibly do.

17:26.433 --> 17:28.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Let's all learn
from this together.

17:28.633 --> 17:32.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And I would be the first to
say that, just as government
needs to do more, we need to

17:32.733 --> 17:35.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ask ourselves what more
we could do as well.

17:35.400 --> 17:38.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Can you
say at this point what
more Microsoft can do?

17:38.733 --> 17:42.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, one of the
issues that I think we need
to think through around the

17:42.766 --> 17:47.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
world is how to help customers,
especially in sophisticated,
diversified, complicated

17:50.533 --> 17:55.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
information technology
environments to deploy
patches more easily.

17:56.966 --> 18:00.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The National Health Service
in the U.K. is a good example.

18:00.300 --> 18:02.100 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's a very large institution.

18:02.100 --> 18:07.100 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Now, in some cases, the
computers are a good deal older.

18:09.000 --> 18:12.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there is certainly
an opportunity for us to ask
ourselves, what new technologies

18:14.233 --> 18:17.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
can we deploy, what new
processes can we develop to
make it easier for customers?

18:18.766 --> 18:21.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then, of course, we
do need customers to act.

18:21.233 --> 18:26.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We cannot actually patch
their systems unless they
deploy our technology.

18:27.400 --> 18:29.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that, too, is a
lesson for us all.

18:29.466 --> 18:31.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I want to go
back to what you were saying
about the role of governments

18:31.566 --> 18:35.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and the role specifically in
this country of the National
Security Agency, the NSA.

18:35.933 --> 18:40.933 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Your point is that they
have developed devices
to fix these flaws that
exist, but they haven't

18:45.033 --> 18:47.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
shared them quickly enough.

18:47.033 --> 18:51.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Were you notified, was
Microsoft notified by
NSA that this was coming?

18:51.133 --> 18:55.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
BRAD SMITH: Well, I don't
want to go into the specifics
of how we learned about this

18:55.666 --> 18:58.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
particular problem
or by whom or when.

18:58.600 --> 19:03.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It is of public record that
we provided a patch in March.

19:03.166 --> 19:07.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
There wasn't a public statement
about this until April.

19:07.300 --> 19:12.300 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what I think is also
important is that we
need the global community
to come together.

19:14.233 --> 19:17.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We called earlier this year
for the creation, in effect,
of a digital Geneva Convention,

19:19.533 --> 19:24.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
new rules of the road that apply
to everybody, because this is
an issue, in this instance,

19:25.933 --> 19:29.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that may have arisen in the
United States, but no one should
think that this is an issue

19:29.266 --> 19:30.900 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
unique to the United States.

19:30.900 --> 19:33.966 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is an issue for many
governments around the world.

19:33.966 --> 19:38.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Brad Smith,
the president of Microsoft, we
thank you very much for joining

19:39.433 --> 19:40.233 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
us.

19:40.233 --> 19:42.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
BRAD SMITH: Thank you.

19:42.200 --> 19:46.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And some further
reporting now on this and
what consumers need to know.

19:47.200 --> 19:49.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And that comes from
William Brangham.

19:49.266 --> 19:52.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And, for
that, we turn to Eric Geller,
who covers cyber-security for

19:52.233 --> 19:53.233 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Politico.

19:53.233 --> 19:54.366 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
Welcome.

19:54.366 --> 19:56.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ERIC GELLER,
Politico: Thank you.

19:56.466 --> 19:58.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, you just
heard the president of Microsoft
make his argument, that they're

19:58.633 --> 20:02.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
not really to blame for
this, for the slowness
or relative slowness, of
putting out the patches.

20:03.866 --> 20:05.900 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do you make of
that point he's making?

20:05.900 --> 20:08.366 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC GELLER: Well, Microsoft
is in a tricky position here,
because, as you heard, he didn't

20:08.366 --> 20:11.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
want to discuss whether they
had been informed by the NSA.

20:11.433 --> 20:13.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Seems likely they were informed.

20:13.500 --> 20:16.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The only other possibility is
that they were told by this
group that leaked the files.

20:16.200 --> 20:18.100 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So, either way, they're
in a tricky situation.

20:18.100 --> 20:21.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
They have got to rush
to fix this problem that
they didn't know about.

20:21.300 --> 20:24.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They're wondering whether they
should demand some changes to
the way the government deals

20:24.333 --> 20:26.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
with these policies.

20:26.433 --> 20:28.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And, of course, at the same
time, they're wondering what
the consequences are going

20:28.033 --> 20:29.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to be for consumers.

20:29.266 --> 20:30.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
So they are in a
tricky situation.

20:30.500 --> 20:32.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think they moved as
fast as they could.

20:32.600 --> 20:35.566 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Of course, what we're seeing
is, the more time you have
to tell customers about the

20:35.566 --> 20:37.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
problem, the more
customers who will fix it.

20:37.766 --> 20:39.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They had only a very
short period of time.

20:39.766 --> 20:42.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And,
obviously, we have been talking
about this potential that the

20:42.800 --> 20:47.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
- - this was somehow a
tool created by the NSA
that was stolen by hackers.

20:49.766 --> 20:52.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And Microsoft is arguing that
that's really the problem,
that the government is devising

20:52.900 --> 20:55.066 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
tools to break
into our computers.

20:55.066 --> 20:59.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Inevitably, those tools
are going to get out,
and we're going to see
the havoc we have seen.

20:59.233 --> 21:01.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
What do you make
of that argument?

21:01.300 --> 21:03.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC GELLER: They certainly have
a point that the U.S. government
has not done a great job

21:03.966 --> 21:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of keeping its secrets secret
over the past few years,
Edward Snowden, Harold Martin,

21:08.233 --> 21:11.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who was recently arrested
and charged with stealing
classified information.

21:11.666 --> 21:13.400 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The Shadow Brokers, we still
don't know who they are.

21:13.400 --> 21:16.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And then, of course, WikiLeaks
has been posting CIA files.

21:16.500 --> 21:18.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
So, look, Microsoft has a point.

21:18.200 --> 21:20.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
The government is not as
good as this as it should be.

21:20.266 --> 21:25.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
On the other hand, the
government needs to
be able to break into
Russian computers, ISIS

21:25.800 --> 21:27.866 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
computers.

21:27.866 --> 21:30.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
There are all kinds of valid
foreign intelligence targets out
there who are using Windows and

21:30.533 --> 21:33.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
who need to be surveilled
by our government in
order to do its job.

21:33.333 --> 21:37.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, I think Microsoft is in a
tricky spot because it doesn't
want to say the government

21:37.033 --> 21:41.166 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
shouldn't be able to
spy on terrorists, but
those same terrorists,
they use the products

21:41.166 --> 21:43.200 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
that we use.

21:43.200 --> 21:45.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And so issues that allow
them to be spied on,
they also put us at risk.

21:45.466 --> 21:48.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Obviously,
that seems like the trickiest
part of the debate.

21:48.433 --> 21:53.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If the government can detect
that there is a hole in a
company's software, do they have

21:55.066 --> 21:57.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
an obligation to tell
that company, so that
they can patch it?

21:57.533 --> 22:02.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
But then that also gives away
the tool that the government
no longer has to do this exact

22:02.033 --> 22:03.033 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
surveillance you're describing.

22:03.033 --> 22:04.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ERIC GELLER: Yes.

22:04.233 --> 22:06.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And the government
has a process.

22:06.333 --> 22:08.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I should say, they have a
process for deciding when to
reveal a flaw to a company.

22:08.233 --> 22:10.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It's called the vulnerability
equities processes.

22:10.300 --> 22:13.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And the government actually
revealed it a few years ago when
there was a major vulnerability

22:13.533 --> 22:15.533 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that was disclosed in public.

22:15.533 --> 22:18.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They still don't have all
the fine-tuning details
of that nailed down.

22:18.600 --> 22:20.666 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And there's been some efforts.

22:20.666 --> 22:24.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
California Democrat Ted Lieu
yesterday said - - or, I should
say, Friday said that he wanted

22:24.200 --> 22:26.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to reform that process.

22:26.300 --> 22:29.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He wanted to change the rules
for when the government has
to tell a company about this.

22:29.033 --> 22:31.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
We're in the very early
stages of this process.

22:31.433 --> 22:33.500 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
This is a very obscure issue.

22:33.500 --> 22:36.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not one that people are
familiar with, but it's one
that, I think, as we saw this

22:36.200 --> 22:38.766 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
weekend, it's becoming more
important to our own lives.

22:38.766 --> 22:42.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Getting
back to this attack
itself, do you think, as
we have been reporting,

22:42.633 --> 22:46.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
that this seems like
it's winding down, or,
as Judy mentioned, are
we see going to more

22:46.466 --> 22:48.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
variants crop up?

22:48.500 --> 22:51.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
ERIC GELLER: It's hard to say,
because, as you point out,
anybody can build a new variant,

22:51.733 --> 22:55.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
anybody can change the code,
put it back out there, and
the ways of sort of killing it

22:55.866 --> 22:59.866 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and tamping down on it, they
have to be pursued freshly,
they have to be pursued anew.

22:59.866 --> 23:02.266 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And so it's possible
that this never stops.

23:02.266 --> 23:05.833 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I have a hard time imagining
that cyber-criminals will
just keep doing this forever.

23:05.833 --> 23:09.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They are going to find other
things that they like to do, but
there is certainly no technical

23:09.300 --> 23:11.000 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
reason that it can't
happen forever.

23:11.000 --> 23:15.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: We saw
this break out first in
hospitals in the U.K.

23:15.533 --> 23:20.533 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Is that because they,
hospitals, are particularly
vulnerable, or was it
because they were targeted

23:21.133 --> 23:22.400 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
specifically?

23:22.400 --> 23:23.666 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
ERIC GELLER: It's
unclear right now.

23:23.666 --> 23:25.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I think they were
probably targeted.

23:25.766 --> 23:28.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
One sort of conspiracy theory
here is that this wasn't meant
to be released when it was,

23:28.733 --> 23:30.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that it was sort of a test.

23:30.766 --> 23:33.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They were trying to figure
out what would happen, and it
got out, and perhaps the way

23:33.466 --> 23:36.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it was initially configured,
it ended up going to the
National Health Service first.

23:36.933 --> 23:40.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Either way, I would say
probably not accidental.

23:40.733 --> 23:42.200 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
These things have to be coded.

23:42.200 --> 23:44.500 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They have got to be targeted
at particular entities.

23:44.500 --> 23:48.300 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's hard for me to imagine that
the scale that we saw with the
NHS, that that was completely

23:48.300 --> 23:50.800 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
random.

23:50.800 --> 23:53.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I should say that
U.S. officials and private
cyber-security firms
have really, I think,

23:53.100 --> 23:55.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
at this point no idea
who it is, although they
are pursuing some leads.

23:55.966 --> 24:00.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Lastly, just
for our viewers out there who
are worried, could this strike

24:00.133 --> 24:05.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
me, what can I do to protect
myself, can you give just us a
quick digital computer hygiene

24:05.966 --> 24:08.000 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
lesson?

24:08.000 --> 24:08.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What are the things people
should do to stop this
from happening to them?

24:08.800 --> 24:10.300 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ERIC GELLER: Yes.

24:10.300 --> 24:12.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I think the number one thing
is, you want to patch Windows.

24:12.300 --> 24:14.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you're running Windows --
and I think a lot of people
out there are -- make sure that

24:14.133 --> 24:16.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you're using -- you should be
running Windows 10, which is...

24:16.900 --> 24:19.066 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: So, when
you get those software update
notifications, do those.

24:19.066 --> 24:21.300 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ERIC GELLER: Do them right away.

24:21.300 --> 24:25.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
You're much better off doing
that and just making sure
that Microsoft is finding all

24:25.700 --> 24:27.633 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the things that could go wrong.

24:27.633 --> 24:29.700 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And just you have got
to install everything
whenever it comes out there.

24:29.700 --> 24:33.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And then also I would say, if
you're running Windows XP --
and I hope to God that very

24:33.500 --> 24:37.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
few of your viewers are running
Windows XP - - but if you are,
you should throw that computer

24:37.266 --> 24:40.800 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
away and get a new one as soon
as possible, because Microsoft
is not going to support

24:40.800 --> 24:43.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
these kind of critical patches
for Windows XP forever.

24:43.233 --> 24:45.733 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: And,
of course, don't click on
those dodgy-looking e-mails.

24:45.733 --> 24:47.233 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ERIC GELLER: Absolutely.

24:47.233 --> 24:51.733 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WILLIAM BRANGHAM: Eric Geller
of Politico, thank you so much.

24:52.733 --> 24:57.033 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
ERIC GELLER: Thank you.

24:57.033 --> 25:02.033 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: North Korea
today hailed its test of a new
intermediate-range missile and

25:04.000 --> 25:08.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
claimed that it can now hit
U.S. bases in the Pacific
with a nuclear warhead.

25:10.033 --> 25:12.266 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
State TV broadcast footage
of Sunday's launch.

25:12.266 --> 25:17.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The missile traveled nearly
500 miles, but analysts said
it could have a maximum range

25:18.033 --> 25:20.166 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
of 2,500 miles.

25:20.166 --> 25:24.966 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
So, just where is the
North in its development
of missile technology
and its nuclear program?

25:26.166 --> 25:28.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
For that, we turn
to Jeffrey Lewis.

25:28.766 --> 25:32.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He's the director of the
East Asia Non-Proliferation
Program at the Middlebury
Institute of International

25:34.000 --> 25:37.166 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Studies in Monterey, California.

25:37.166 --> 25:39.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Jeffrey Lewis, thank you
very much for joining us.

25:39.900 --> 25:43.833 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
This sounds like quite
an advance on the part
of the North Koreans.

25:43.833 --> 25:46.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Tell us more about
this missile test.

25:46.133 --> 25:48.600 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
What exactly was it yesterday?

25:48.600 --> 25:50.133 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JEFFREY LEWIS, Director,
East Asia Non-Proliferation
Program, Monterey
Institute of International

25:50.133 --> 25:52.300 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Studies: Well, it's a
brand-new type of missile.

25:52.300 --> 25:56.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We'd seen a version of this
in a parade just a month ago,
but what's really striking is,

25:56.633 --> 26:00.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
it seems to use a new
engine that the North
Koreans designed themselves.

26:00.166 --> 26:03.633 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in the past, normally,
they have copied engines
from other places.

26:03.633 --> 26:08.200 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This looks like the first engine
that's fully North Korean, so
it's a big step forward for

26:08.200 --> 26:09.666 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
them.

26:09.666 --> 26:10.800 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what does
that mean, a new engine?

26:10.800 --> 26:13.566 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
Does that mean
distance, power, what?

26:13.566 --> 26:16.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
®MD-BJEFFREY LEWIS: Well, what
it really means is know-how.

26:16.900 --> 26:20.533 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
And so, ultimately,
that will translate
into distance and power.

26:20.533 --> 26:24.966 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, in the past, the North
Koreans, by copying missiles, if
we have asked this question can

26:24.966 --> 26:29.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you build an ICBM, we have
had to imagine how they could
cobble together an ICBM using

26:29.466 --> 26:32.666 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
parts and pieces from other
engines they have copied.

26:32.666 --> 26:36.833 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now it looks like they
actually have the design
expertise to build this
kind of missile themselves,

26:36.833 --> 26:40.433 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and I think in the future that
should lead us toward an ICBM.

26:40.433 --> 26:45.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, as I said in
the introduction, 500 miles, but
the experts are saying it could

26:46.766 --> 26:48.766 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
potentially be 2,500 miles.

26:48.766 --> 26:52.166 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
I mean, what is the
potential capacity of this?

26:52.166 --> 26:54.233 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
®MD-BJEFFREY LEWIS: Right.

26:54.233 --> 26:59.133 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Well, so what the North Koreans
did was, they shot it almost
straight up, because they didn't

26:59.133 --> 27:01.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
want to fire it at Alaska.

27:01.400 --> 27:03.500 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
They didn't want it
to overfly Japan.

27:03.500 --> 27:07.766 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And so, while it only
traveled -- sorry -- I
have to do kilometers --
while it only traveled

27:07.766 --> 27:12.766 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
about 800 kilometers downrange,
it went more than 2,000
kilometers up into space, which

27:14.500 --> 27:16.533 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is much higher than,
for example, the
International Space Station.

27:16.533 --> 27:20.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, if they had straightened it
out, it would have been like a
4,500-kilometer range, which

27:20.433 --> 27:22.466 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
would be nearly an
ICBM, but not quite.

27:22.466 --> 27:26.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, that
means they can reach where
-- could reach where?

27:26.500 --> 27:29.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
®MD-BJEFFREY LEWIS:
That missile would just
fall short of Alaska.

27:29.633 --> 27:34.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So,
U.S. land, territory.

27:36.500 --> 27:40.600 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Is this -- and your point is
that this is - - it's technology
that the North Koreans,

27:41.800 --> 27:45.333 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
as far as we know, have
only gained recently?

27:45.333 --> 27:48.200 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
®MD-BJEFFREY LEWIS:
Well, that's right.

27:48.200 --> 27:51.266 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
In the past, they have mostly
copied other countries' engines,
and so there's been kind

27:51.266 --> 27:55.466 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of a problem with quality
and a real limit on what
they could do with that.

27:55.466 --> 27:59.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
This is probably a breakthrough,
in the sense that, now they
have that design expertise

27:59.433 --> 28:04.433 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on their own, they will be able
to continually improve and make
longer -- longer-range missiles.

28:06.933 --> 28:09.633 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I was
reading that this says a
lot about their ability
potentially to miniaturize

28:11.600 --> 28:15.933 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a warhead, about the ability of
the missile to survive reentry
into the Earth's atmosphere,

28:17.366 --> 28:19.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
once it goes up into space,
comes back down again.

28:19.900 --> 28:22.400 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
I'm assuming all of
that is significant.

28:22.400 --> 28:25.433 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But they haven't
perfected it yet.

28:25.433 --> 28:28.900 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
What are the hurdles that
they still need to overcome?

28:28.900 --> 28:33.900 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
®MD-BJEFFREY LEWIS: Well,
what they have done are test
all of the parts and pieces.

28:35.300 --> 28:37.233 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, for example, we have
seen this new large engine.

28:37.233 --> 28:40.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have also seen North
Koreans test a different engine
that would work in an ICBM.

28:40.000 --> 28:45.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have seen them do
ground tests of the -- it's
called a reentry vehicle.

28:46.966 --> 28:49.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's basically the ability
to bring the warhead
back into the atmosphere.

28:49.000 --> 28:53.500 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, really, what North Korea
has to do is put all those
things together and test them

28:53.500 --> 28:55.166 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
at once.

28:55.166 --> 28:57.700 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
So, that's still in the
future, but it's not
very far in the future.

28:57.700 --> 28:59.733 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What do
you mean not very far?

28:59.733 --> 29:04.666 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
®MD-BJEFFREY LEWIS: They could
